  						<!--#beginContent#-->
  						<table align=center cellpadding='3' width='85%'>
  <tr><td class='spti2'>PLAYER JOURNAL</td></tr>  <tr><td class='db'><font class='dbti'>The Journey to the Icy Scars Part II</font> - Sainomi Crescentwind</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'> </td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db'>It was a dangerous risk I took, but I did it anyway, I knew I was probably safer with this man then I would have been alone. It wasn't like he was of Cazic Thule or of the Teir Dal. Just a Human, a lowly human. I used the Invisiblity song to get us though most of the perrils of Ice, such as the giants and the iceburg hopping. I must give my gratitude to the great bard who wrote this song. Thank you! Anyway, upon crossing the second iceburg the clouds grew thicker and the snow began to pour, I looked up at the heavens and I knew I was angry with the Rainkeeper Karana. The winds blew hard as I covered myself with my Cloak I got from a traveling man in Freeport. Twas called The Cloak of the Icebear he said, and was I glad I had it. Crossing the eastern wastelands the dark knight told me about how his mother was a paladin and she disappeared, and how he once trainned to be a paladin like her but the pain he lived caused him to fall into his haunting disposition, I can't say I didn't feel bad for the poor misguided knight. I saw some of the collosal giants from afar, it was amazing to see, frightening, they were ever bigger then those of Kunark. Then I marveled at the river, the huge river splitting the entire great divide. The Shadowknight followed the grand river until we reached a giant waterfall. He told me that the city was behind it. I didn't believe him, but he sounded so serious. Then I saw it, a high elven woman walk behind the waterfall and disappear into the icy wall behind it. I was amazed. Then he did the same thing. So I closed my eyes tight and just ran at the wall, I went through. He told me it was probably the workmof an enchanter, and it is for protection purposes. I walked down the frozen hallway until I came to a bridge. I was in the magnificent city of Thurgadin! I was so happy I had lived through the journey when my enemy was nature itself. The dwarves were not like the ones I grew up knowing. They had more bulk and were pale, probably from the harsh weather. I walked into the first Bar I saw ready to celebrate my arrival after I bid farewell to the misguided knight who I hoped to see again. The bar was three floors, a lobby, bar, and an inn. This bar was called The Broken Glacier. After spending a while here I got to know the locals of the tavern and the one dwarf pulled me aside and told me that the bar needed a good bard to attract more people and to liven the place up. I sang for the man and he told me he would make a deal with the innkeep upstairs to give me a free room to live in on the top floor if I would play there and work in the bar. I took the little guy up on his offer. Now I reside on the third floor of the Broken Glacier tavern and inn. They have the best iced beer I have ever had before. I knew I was at my new home, even if it was a little chilly, and I even got a job. The next day I planned to promote the new bar I worked with and explore the rest of the town. I can't wait to hit the library and speak with the loremasters to learn more about this amazing land and city. and I urge anyone in Thurgadin to buy from the broken glacier, who knows, you might run into me and we can talk over a nice ale. Now I curl up in my bed on the third floor, blow out the candle and drift off to sleep, I am at home now...</td></tr>
  <tr><td class='db2'><a href='view_profile.asp?Action=Journal&Id=72042'>Return to Sainomi's Journal</a></td></tr>
</table>
